        "text": "Berlin and Bolton calendars 6:00 AM Feb 9, 2018 at 7:24 PM\nBERLIN\nFebruary Events: at the Berlin Public Library, 23 Carter St. Valentine Card Making, drop-in craft, 10 a.m.-12:30 p.m. Saturday, Feb. 10. All ages. Valentine’s Party, 10:30 a.m. Monday, Feb. 12. Stories, Valentine crafts and treats. All ages. Groovy Pete the Cat Story, 10:30 a.m. Tuesday, Feb. 20. Books and edible crafts. Kids Knit with Katelyn, 1-2 p.m. Tuesday, Feb. 20. Sip and Paint pARTy, 10:30 a.m. Wednesday, Feb. 21; 19 Carter. Ages 5 and older. Sip hot cocoa and paint snowmen. Register for a canvas by Thursday, Feb. 14. Creatively Cursive with Laurel, 11 a.m. Thursday, Feb. 22. Build and develop this life skill. Cursive activities are personalized and age-appropriate for kids from elementary to high school. Registration appreciated, drop-ins welcome. Origami Workshop with Alex, 1 p.m. Thursday, Feb. 22. Drop-in. Ages 7 and older.\nTech Help with Parker and Davis: 10 a.m.-noon Saturdays, Feb. 10, March 10, April 14, May 19, Sept. 8, Oct. 13, Nov. 10, Dec. 8; Berlin Public Library, 19 Carter. Free help with phones, tablets, overdrive, passwords, social media and more. Schedule is subject to change, check the library's calendar at www.townofberlin.com for updates.\nAdult Clinic: 9:30-11:30 a.m. Thursday, Feb. 15; Senior Housing, 600 Main St. No appointment needed. For information, contact Nashoba Associated Boards of Health at (978) 772-3335 or (800) 427-9762, ext. 340, or visit www.nashoba.org.Meet with the nurse for a wellness check including blood pressure/pulse monitoring, blood sugar screening, general health counseling and further assessments with referrals as needed. Hosted by Nashoba Associated Boards of Health in conjunction with the Bolton Board of Health.\nMany Hands Thrift Shoppe: First Parish Church of Berlin, 24 Central St., Route 62. Cash only. Donation dropoff and hours, 10 a.m.-2 p.m. Tuesdays, noon-8 p.m. Thursdays and 10 a.m.-2 p.m. the first and third Saturday of the month.\nSpecial Education Services Child Find: is an effort to identify and provide services to Berlin and Boylston children with special education needs. Direct written inquires to Karen Molnar, Director of Pupil Personnel Services, Berlin and Boylston Public Schools, 215 Main St., Boylston, MA 01505, or call (508) 869-2837, ext. 1106. The Berlin and Boylston Public School Systems invite parents of public and private school-age children, ages 3-21, to contact the schools' special education office for information regarding the special education screening referral process, eligibility criteria for special education and special education services.\nBOLTON\nCensus Forms: have been mailed to all residents. For information or assistance, call (978) 779-2771 or email townclerk@townofbolton.com. Review your data, make any changes and return the signed census to the town clerk's office within 10 days of receiving it. The form may also be emailed by scanning it or taking a photo with a phone and sending it to census@townofbolton.com.\nChildren's Happenings: Bolton Public Library, 738 Main St. For information, call (978) 779-2839. Family Movie, \"Beauty and the Beast,\" 1:30-3:45 p.m. Friday, Feb. 9. Frozen Crafts and Movie, Tuesday, Feb 20. All ages can register for \"Frozen\"-themed crafts from 1-2 p.m., or drop in to the Program Room from 2-2:30 p.m. for the movie \"Olaf's Frozen Adventure.\" Register for crafts at www.boltonpubliclibrary.org/calendar. Anime Club Meeting, 4-5 p.m. Tuesday, Feb. 20. Ages 12 to 18. 3D Printing Workshop, 10:30 a.m.-12:30 p.m. Thursday, Feb. 22. Arthur Evans is returning with his popular 3D printing program. Register at www.boltonpubliclibrary.org/calendar. Ages 8 to 14. Drop-In Teen DIY, 3-5 p.m. Thursday, Feb. 22. Teens can come make Shrinky Dink \"enamel\" pins.\nBolton Public Access TV: Feb. 11-17, airing on Channel 8: Valentine’s-themed shows. Graceful Aging, a show about improving our lives as we age and About’s Valentine’s Special. Wednesday, Feb. 14, old movies all day, including Charade, Jane Eyre, The Last of the Belles and more. For schedules and updates, visit www.boltonaccess.tv.\n‘Summer Dreams’ Concert: presented by the Nashoba Symphonic Band, 3 p.m. Sunday, Feb. 11; Nashoba Regional High School Auditorium, 12 Green Road. Snow date, 7 p.m. Thursday, Feb. 15. Free. For information, visit www.nashobamusic.com. The band will perform John Philip Sousa’s \"Manhattan Beach,\" John Barnes Chance’s \"Blue Lake Overture,\" \"Berceuse and Finale\" from Igor Stravinsky’s “The Firebird,\"’ Hagen’s \"Harlem Nocturne\" and selections from “Carousel.”\nTuesday Connection Presentation: 11 a.m.-1 p.m. Tuesday, Feb. 20; Bolton Senior Center, 600 Main St. For information, call Mary at (978) 779-5145. The Bolton Historical Society presents a video program produced by Bolton Access TV featuring Bolton resident Ruea Baum. Baum shares her story of growing up in Bolton and serving as a U.S. Army nurse in England and France during World War II. The program will be followed by lunch of soup and sandwiches, with cupcakes for dessert.\nRed Cross Blood Drive: 1-6 p.m. Thursday, Feb. 22; Trinity Church, 14 Wattaquadock Hill Road. For an appointment, call (800) 733-2767 or visit RedCrossBlood.org. Walk-ins welcome.\nRegistered Democrats Caucus: to elect delegates and alternates to the 2018 Massachusetts Democratic State Convention, 7 p.m. Tuesday, Feb. 27; Bolton Public Library Program Room, 738 Main St. For information, contact Bolton DTC chair Jim Carvalho at (978) 779-2274 or jbcarvalho@verizon.net. The Convention will be nominating candidates for all state offices, including governor, lieutenant governor, secretary of state, treasurer, and U.S. Senator. The state convention will be held Saturday, June 2, at the DCU Center in Worcester. The caucus is open to all registered and pre-registered Democrats in Bolton. Pre-registered Democrats are persons who will be 18 by Sept. 18. You can register as a Democrat at the Caucus. Those not elected as delegate or alternate who meet the qualifications may apply to be add-on delegates in the following categories: youth, minority, disabled and LGBTQ.\n2019 District Budget Hearing: held by the Nashoba Regional School Committee, 6 p.m. Wednesday, Feb. 28; Emerson School, 50 Mechanic St., Conference Room.\nOpen Burning Season: A new burning permit must be obtained each season. Directions on obtaining a burning permit can be found under the fire prevention/fire department page at http://www.townofbolton.com/fire-department. No fee. Burning season ends Tuesday, May 1.\nTom Denney Nature Camp Registration: is open at tdnc.boltonconservationtrust.org. For information, visit tdnc.boltonconservationtrust.org, email bcttdnc@gmail.com or call (978) 429-3004. The camp is for students entering grades 1 through 8, and offers five weekly sessions of fun and learning in Bolton's Bowers Springs conservation area. Campers entering grades 6 through 8 may choose the Eco Adventures program, where they will explore the wildlife of Bolton while learning how to safely and responsibly enjoy the outdoors. Applicants for Counselor in Training must be entering Grade 9 or above. Weekly sessions run 9 a.m.-3 p.m. Monday, July 9, to Friday, Aug. 10 (Monday-Friday). There is no residency requirement.\nVolunteer Positions Available: The town is seeking volunteers for the following boards and committees: Affordable Housing Partnership Trust Fund (2), Board of Appeals – Associate (1), Capital Planning Committee (3), Conservation Commission (2), Cultural Council (5), Economic Development Committee (1), Historical Commission (1), Human Services and Safety Committee (2), Insurance Advisory Committee (3), Planning Board – Associate (1), Public Ways Safety Committee (1), Town Roads Strategic Planning Committee (1), Water Resource Subcommittee (2). Interested individuals should send a letter of interest to Linda Day at secretary@townofbolton.com or Bolton Town Hall, 663 Main St., Bolton, MA 01740.\nVolunteers Sought: to represent the town and as an alternate on the Nashua River Wild and Scenic Rivers Study Committee. Meetings are the third Thursday of the month from 7 to 9 p.m. at the Nashua River Watershed Association (NRWA) in Groton. For information, visit http://WildandScenicNashuaRivers.org or email Linda Day at secretary@townofbolton.com. The study will determine whether the Nashua River Mainstem, Squannacook River and/or the Nissitissit River segment is eligible and suitable for “Wild and Scenic” designation.\nNashoba Regional School District: needs help identifying all children in the community, ages 3 to 21, who may require special education or 504 services. If you are aware of a child who has or may have an educational disability, who may not be known to the district, call the Special Education Department at (978) 779-0539, ext. 3013.",
