        "title": "Around Danvers",
        "text": "Feb 8, 2018 at 8:00 AM \nUpcoming \nBlood donation opportunity: 12:45-6:15 p.m. Feb. 8 and 12-15; 8:30 a.m.-2 p.m. Feb. 9-11, Danvers Blood Donation Center, 99 Rosewood Drive. Make an appointment to give blood or platelets by downloading the free Red Cross Blood Donor App, visiting http://redcrossblood.org or calling 800-733-2767. More than 550 blood drives have been forced to cancel due to winter weather in January, causing over 16,500 blood and platelet donations to go uncollected. In Massachusetts, 28 blood drives have been forced to cancel due to winter weather this month, causing 750 donations to go uncollected. In addition, bitter cold and widespread flu have contributed to very low turnout at many blood drives. Every day, no matter the weather, the Red Cross must collect more than 13,000 blood and platelet donations to meet the needs of patients. \nValentine’s SpaTacular: 6-9:30 a.m. Feb. 8, Breakaway, 221 Newbury St. Route 1 North, Danvers. Cost: $20-$25. For information: https://facebook.com/events/1293453104093892/. The SPAtacular event is for women ages 21 and up. A cash bar and restaurant are available on site. This event will feature local products and services. Dellaria of Danvers will be providing blowouts, curls and updos. Attendees will find skincare, jewelry, essential oils, candles and makeup vendors, sweet and more. Only participants with a ticket will be allowed into the hall. The event is hosting a handbag drive; bring a new or gently used handbag to the event. \nRed Cross Blood drive: 12:45 p.m.-6:15 p.m. Feb. 8-9, Danvers Blood Donation Center, 99 Rosewood Drive. Make an appointment to give blood by using the app, visiting http://redcrossblood.org, or calling 1-800-733-2767. With the free Red Cross Blood Donor App, donors can schedule and manage donation appointments, access their donor card, track the impact of their donations and earn rewards. Donors can also save up to 15 minutes at the blood drive by using RapidPass to complete their pre-donation reading and health history questions online at http://redcrossblood.org/RapidPass before coming to their appointments. \nAmericanism Award: 7 p.m. Feb. 8, VFW Hall, 5 Conant St., Danvers. The Drapeau-McPhetres American Legion Post 180, of Danvers, will be presenting their Bruce P. Eaton Annual Americanism Award. The recipients will be Bill and Lois McKenzie, of Danvers, who are being recognized for their countless efforts and activities aiding veterans and the local community. This award was formerly known as the Annual Americanism Award, but was renamed the Bruce P. Eaton Americanism Award in honor of Eaton’s dedicated service to veterans spanning over 70 years. The general public and past recipients are invited to attend. \nDemocratic Committee caucus: 7 p.m. Feb. 8, Polish Club, Cheever St., Danvers. For information, contact Chairperson Marilyn Hazel at 978-590-1473 or hazel_marilyn@hahoo.com. The Danvers Democratic Committee will be holding a caucus to elect 12 delegates, comprised of six males and six females, along with four alternate delegates, two males and two females, to attend the State Democratic Endorsing Convention at the DCU Center in Worcester on June 1 and 2. Anyone interested in running to be a delegate or alternate delegate must be present at the caucus by 7 p.m. \nLittle Falcons — Danvers Integrated Preschool Peer Partner Screening: Feb. 9, Riverside Elementary, 95 Liberty St., Danvers. An appointment time can be scheduled by calling the Department of Student Services at 978-774-6112. Danvers Integrated Preschool is now enrolling ages 3-5 for current preschool programs for children who will be age 3 by April 2018. The Preschool is located at Riverside Elementary School. Peer Partner Screening is a 20-minute playgroup, during which a child’s language, social, physical and cognitive development will be informally screened as part of the enrollment process. A lottery system is used to complete the final selection of students when the number of applicants exceeds the number of openings. Classes meet four days a week from 8:30-11 a.m. Tuesdays and Fridays and from 11:35 a.m.-2 p.m. Monday and Thursdays. \nDanvers Rail Trail Chocolate Walk: 11 a.m. Feb. 10, Hobart Street, Danvers. For information: http://danversrailtrail.org. Join the Danvers Rail Trail Committee for its third Chocolate Walk led by committee member Charles Lincicum. The group will meet at the Hobart Street parking lot and then walk north to Putnamville Park and return on the same route. This route is approximately 3 miles round trip. “Chocolate stops” will be available at different points along the walk. Children, and dogs on leashes, are welcome. Walkers with dogs will be asked to depart a bit after 11 a.m. in order to minimize congestion on the trail. The committee recommends that walkers come prepared with the right footwear and outerwear. Bring along anti-skid straps for boots in case sections of the trail are icy. The Danvers Rail Trail is an all-volunteer organization. Donations to support this event and the maintenance of the trail are always welcome. \nSilent Movie Night —”Ella Cinders”: 7:15 p.m. Feb. 10, Maple Street Church, 90 Maple St., Danvers. Cost: $5 per person; $15 per family. For information: 978-774-4510; http://maplestreetchurch.org. Maple Street Church Coffee House will screen the 1926 silent film “Ella Cinders,” which features Colleen Moore. Moore put her stamp on American social history, creating in dozens of films the image of the wide-eyed flapper with bobbed hair and short skirts. The plot revolves around Ella, who, in spite of her wicked stepmother, enters a contest and wins a trip to Hollywood. She was featured in dozens of films starting in 1917 and near the end of her career, she starred with Spencer Tracy in a talkie titled “The Power and the Glory.” Returning to accompany the silent film will be pianist Robert Humphreville. Refreshments will be available, including popcorn. \nSen. Joan Lovely office hours: 9-10 a.m. Feb. 12, April 9, June 11, Aug. 13 and Oct. 22, Danvers Council on Aging, 25 Stone St.; 9-10 a.m. March 12, May 14, July 9 and Sept. 10, Brother’s Deli, 31 Maple St., Danvers. For information, call 617-722-1410. Sen. Joan Lovely, D-Salem, has announced her Danvers office hours. \nDine to Donate: 4-10 p.m. Feb. 12, Texas Roadhouse, 301 Newbury St., Danvers. For information, a list of locations and a copy of the promotional flyer, visit http://massri.wish.org/DinetoDonate. Make-A-Wish Massachusetts and Rhode Island have partnered with Texas Roadhouse for the “Dine to Donate” event to help grant life-changing wishes for children with critical illnesses. Dine at select Texas Roadhouse throughout Massachusetts and Rhode Island on Feb. 12 and 10 percent of total food purchases will be donated to Make-A-Wish Massachusetts and Rhode Island. Diners must present the “Dine to Donate” promotional flyer to participate; diners may also show the flyer on their phone. Valid on dine-in and take out. In addition, a Make-A-Wish volunteer will be available to accept donations to the charity at participating locations between 4-8 p.m. \nJim McCoy author visit: 7-8:30 a.m. Feb. 15, Peabody Institute Library of Danvers, 15 Sylvan St., Danvers. Register at www.danverslibrary.org or by calling 978-774-0554. Join life coach Jim McCoy as he speaks on his self-help book “The Last Place You Look: A Contrarian’s Guide to Dating and Finding Love.” This event is free and open to the public. \nNSCC Supervisors’ Connection Workshop: 8-10 a.m. Feb. 21, North Shore Community College Danvers campus, 1 Ferncroft Road, DS106. Cost: $49. For information and registration: 978-236-1240. The workshop will focus on “Leader Blind Spots and Hidden Strengths.” \nConnections book group: 7 p.m. March 14, Putnam Pantry, 255 Newbury St., Danvers. Mothers of PJ Library, past and current, are invited to Lappin Foundation’s book group Connections. Attendees will discuss Sabra Waldfogel’s book “Sister of Mine: A Novel” and enjoy a sundae buffet. This is a free event. To register for Connections and to order a free book, contact Phyllis Osher at 978-740-4404 or email posher@lappinfoundation.org with the choice of paperback book or Kindle. \nOngoing \nCelebrate Recovery: 7-8:30 p.m. Mondays, 63 Jefferson Ave., Salem; noon–1:30 p.m. Fridays, 75 Lindal St., Danvers. For information: 617-803-4589. Celebrate Recovery is now holding free and open groups for anyone who would like to drop by. Celebrate Recovery is a Christian 12-step recovery program for hurts, habits, hangups and addictions. \nTai Chi: 10 a.m Tuesdays —”Step by Step”; 9:30 a.m. Thursdays —“Beginner Foundations; 11 a.m. Tuesdays —”Intermediate Sword.” Tapley Memorial Hall, 13 Page St., Danvers. For information and to RSVP: 978-314-4264 Johanna Hattendorf leads tai chi classes — participants will strengthen joints, improve balance, breathing and concentration, and decrease stress. \n“Acoustics Only” musicians program: 7-9 p.m. every third Wednesday, beginning Nov. 15, Tapley Memorial Hall, 13 Page St., Danvers. For information: 978-777-2711. The “Acoustics Only” musicians program will encourage audience participation. This event is free and open to the public and is sponsored by the Danvers Historical Society. \nVeterans Social: 4:30–6:30 p.m. every Thursday, VFW Hall, 5 Conant St., Danvers. For information: 978-836-2395. All veterans and their families, regardless of military branch, dates of service or location of assignments are welcome. Food and drink are served; guest speakers will provide current information on important veteran-related issues. \nOvereaters Anonymous: 7–8 p.m. Mondays at All Saints Episcopal Church, 46 Cherry St., Danvers. OA is a free, 12-step support group for people with eating disorders. For information: 781-641-2303. \nTeen Book Corps: 3:30–5:30 p.m. third Mondays, Peabody Institute Library West Branch, 603 Lowell St. For information and registration: http://peabodylibrary.org. Middle and high school students are invited to join the Peabody Institute Library’s new Teen Book Corps, a community service group for ages 11–18 whose mission is to spread a love of books and reading in the Peabody community. All meeting hours count toward community service requirements. \nWeekly screenings by Heritage Films: 7:15 p.m. Tuesdays, Salem Access TV Studios, 285 Derby St., Salem; and monthly at Peabody Institute Library, 15 Sylvan St., Danvers. For information, call 978-777-2711. Heritage Independent Films presents short, locally made documentaries not seen as usual film fare in local theatrical settings. Dan Tremblay produces this series. The films vary in topic, including history, mystery and local special events. \nMulti-sensory music program—singing and signing: 10:30–11:15 a.m. first Wednesdays of each month, Peabody Institute Library South Branch, 78 Lynn St., Peabody. Registration required. For information: 978-531-3380; http://peabodylibrary.org. \nThe Northshoremen: 7:30–10:30 p.m. Wednesdays, Italian Community Center, 300 Rantoul St., Beverly. For information: 508-397-4444. Men of all ages invited to learn four-part harmony with The Northshoremen. \nOpen mic night: 8:30 p.m. Thursdays, Maple Street Tavern, 49 Maple St., Danvers. For information: facebook.com/pages/Maple-Street-Tavern/231976953487000. \nBoy Scout Troop 50 meetings: 7–8:30 p.m. Thursdays, St. Mary of the Annunciation Parish Hall, 24 Conant St., Danvers. For information: 978-994-9555; troop50.georgetownboyscouts@gmail.com. Troop meetings have started for the new scouting year. Boys ages 10 and over may join, whether or not they have previously participated in Cub Scouts. \nDanvers Community Access Television weekend classes: 9 a.m. to 1 p.m. Saturdays, 87 Elm St., Danvers. For information: 978-777-2720. DCAT is open every Saturday. Area residents are invited to edit, tape shows or take classes. Sign up for daily e-mails",
