        "title": "Leyden basketball team raises money for school employee with cancer - Franklin Park Herald-Journal",
        "text": "Barb Marinello has worked in the East Leyden cafeteria for the last decade, serving food to students and teachers each school day with a friendly disposition.\nMarinello hasn't been at work since before the holidays, though, after she was diagnosed over winter break with multiple myeloma, a type of blood cancer that develops in plasma cells, which are mainly found in bone marrow.\nIn response, Leyden boys basketball coach Bill Heisler and his squad selected Marinello, a 1975 East Leyden graduate, as the recipient for the team's annual Coaches vs. Cancer fundraiser.\nThe #Ballin4Barb event was held Friday in conjunction with Leyden's West Suburban Gold home game versus Proviso East, which the Eagles lost 74-47 in Franklin Park. The fundraiser not only netted $9,250 for Marinello to use toward her medical expenses, according to Heisler, it also showed the collective strength that a school community can exhibit.\n\"I can't put into words what this means to me, to have so many people go to these lengths to help me,\" said Marinello, who attended the game. \"I'm used to taking care of other people, so it's been a little hard to accept. But wonderful.\"\nThere were several layers of fundraising employed the week of the event, the most visible being the white \"Crush Cancer\" T-shirts that dotted the boisterous crowd.\nFor $10, people got the T-shirt and admission to the game, where $1 donation cards were also available. The T-shirts and cards raised $2,250, according to Heisler, and the food services staff raised $4,000 by selling raffle tickets during lunch periods and at the game for 64 donated gift baskets.\nEric P. Davis / Pioneer Press Leyden boys basketball coach Bill Heisler wears a “Crush Cancer” T-shirt during the Feb. 2, 2018 game against Proviso East in Franklin Park.\nLeyden boys basketball coach Bill Heisler wears a “Crush Cancer” T-shirt during the Feb. 2, 2018 game against Proviso East in Franklin Park.\n(Eric P. Davis / Pioneer Press) In addition, the local Unity in Community Foundation pledged to match up to $1,000 in funds raised.\n\"Barb is such a sweet, upbeat lady and the love that she gives every day is the biggest reason so many people have gotten behind this cause,\" said Heisler, now in his 11th year as Leyden's head coach. \"Everyone has really embraced this.\"\nSoon after her diagnosis, Marinello began treatment, which includes radiation therapy and twice-weekly chemotherapy sessions at Alexian Brothers Medical Center in Elk Grove Village. She also takes medication daily. Her first treatment cycle is slated to end Thursday, at which time Marinello will take a week off before launching into another 28-day round.\n\"The radiation was absolutely terrible, and I've had to incorporate some different things lifestyle-wise, like changing my eating habits,\" Marinello said. \"But I've felt such an outpouring of love. The people here are like a second family.\"\nPart of that family includes Leyden's players.\nJunior point guard Kyler Britten didn't need any prodding to be all-in on #Ballin4Barb.\nIt wasn't long after he arrived on campus as a freshman that he came to expect Marinello's upbeat demeanor during what can sometimes be long, stressful school days.\n\"If she sees a kid not smiling, she'll crack a joke to make them feel welcome and happy,\" said Britten, a Franklin Park resident who scored 12 points in the loss. \"You don't really see a lot of people like her nowadays. She's a friend that you want to have in your life because she always makes you feel better.\"\nOn Friday night the Leyden community attempted to return the favor.\nSteve Reaven is a freelance reporter for Pioneer Press.\nTwitter @Pioneer_Press\nWhat is your first, worst, thirst car? Volunteers shovel snow in Chicago Time-lapse shows winter storm bringing snow to Chicago Copyright © 2018, Chicago Tribune Coaches Cancer",
