        "title": "This region is bottom of the league when it comes to organ donation",
        "text": "This region is bottom of the league when it comes to organ donation The East Midlands gave 74 organs for donation in a year Share Click to play Tap to play The video will start in 8 Cancel Play now Get Daily updates directly to your inbox + Subscribe Thank you for subscribing! Could not subscribe, try again later Invalid Email \nA new survey has revealed that residents in the East Midlands are at the bottom of the league when it comes to organ donation. \nIn a year, people in the whole of the region donated 74 organs while folk in the North West gave 162 organs. \nThe figure for the East Midlands represents just 15.8 people per million population donating organs during that year - the lowest in England. Doctor in operating theatre (Image: Getty) \nThe report showed that people in the North-West gave the highest number of organs - 162, representing 22.6 donors per million. \nThis per capita figure was only topped by the North-East where 28.6 people per million donated - the highest such percentage nationwide. Read More \nCystic Fibrosis sufferer Charlotte Davies, whose life was saved by a lung transplant, urged people to join the organ donor register. \nThe grateful 24-year-old said: “Organ donation is an incredible act of kindness. Surgeon and nurse suture patient (Image: Getty) \n“In 2011 my life was saved thanks to my amazing donor and her family, who agreed to fulfil my donor’s wish to donate in the event of death. \n“Struggling to breathe due to Cystic Fibrosis, my lung transplant gave me the chance to graduate from university, jump out of a plane and enjoy every moment life gives. \n“Without organ donation I would have died at 18 years old. “I urge everyone who has the desire to sign up to the register, to do so and please share your wishes with your loved ones.” \nThe statistics were revealed in research carried out for the fitness experts Nuyoo , using the NHS Organ Donation and Transplantation Activity Report for 2016/17. Kidneys are important for blood purification in the body (Image: Getty) \nThe same survey revealed that the number of deceased organ donors rose to 1,413, a four percent increase on the previous year . \nIn addition, there were 1,043 living donors. Read More Money Saving Expert Martin Lewis: every single tip from 2018 so far \nThis saw 753 live-saving and life-transforming transplants being performed by surgeons. \nIt was also revealed that the NHS succeeded in reaching a milestone figure, with 50,000 people alive today thanks to a transplant. \nHowever, there were 6,388 patients waiting for a life-saving transplant in 2017. \nSadly, 457 patients died while waiting for their transplant on the active list, while 875 were removed from the list altogether. \nThe removals were mostly due to deteriorating health and ineligibility for transplant – with many of these patients passing away shortly after. Read More Giant jars of Nutella being sold at crazy prices as two supermarkets try to woo customers \nThe North West was found to donate the most kidneys and cardiothoracic organs. \nWhile pancreas donation numbers are highest in the West Midlands, the East of England is highest for liver donations. Like us on Facebook ",
