        "title": "Hanover Township donor gives blood to honor relatives who battled cancer - The Morning Call",
        "text": "You don’t need a reason to donate blood. But if you did, Dave Caine has two.\nBoth his grandfather and his stepfather suffered from leukemia. His grandfather succumbed to the illness. His stepfather beat it and has been in remission for 11 years. Caine donates not only blood but blood platelets, which cancer patients often need, to honor his relatives.\nCaine, of Hanover Township, Northampton County, is one of several people who reached out to me after reading my column a few weeks ago recounting how I started donating blood again after more than a decade of sitting on the sidelines. He thanked me for getting the word out and agreed to share his story to inspire people to donate platelets, too.\n“It’s definitely something that’s needed,” he told me Thursday over lunch in Bethlehem.\nPlatelets are cells that play an important role in controlling bleeding and bruising. Some cancer patients require daily platelet transfusions for several weeks because they become anemic and lose platelets during their treatments, according to the Miller-Keystone Blood Center’s website.\nCaine said his stepfather, Don Goldstein, went through that. He recalled hearing stories about how “every day he’s getting a unit of platelets.”\nPlatelets also are important for burn and accident victims, heart surgery patients, organ and bone marrow transplant patients, premature babies and others.\nCaine remembers his father donating platelets and he followed his lead. But it took on a new meaning when Goldstein was diagnosed with leukemia, a cancer of blood cells.\n“With Don, that kind of strengthened the reason why I want to do it,” Caine said.\nPlatelets can be donated more frequently than blood and Caine tries to give every eight weeks. He said as he’s leaving the Miller-Keystone Blood Center, he’ll call Goldstein — whom he refers to as his “bonus dad” instead of as his stepfather — to tell him he donated again and was thinking of him.\n“It’s a little sappy,” he said.\nHe doesn’t know much about his grandfather, Murray Caine. He died when Caine’s father was 2. But he donates in his honor as well.\nDonating platelets is different than donating blood. It takes longer, 90 minutes to two hours. An automated system known as apheresis separates your blood into its components — red blood cells, platelets and plasma. Your platelets are collected while your red blood cells and plasma are returned to your body.\nOur bodies reproduce platelets rapidly, so donors can give every eight days, instead of every 56 days for whole blood donations. There is a limit of 24 platelet donations a year, according to Miller-Keystone Blood Center’s website.\nPlatelets have a short shelf life, though, and last only five days. So donors always are needed.\nPaul Muschick I donated blood this week for the first time in a long time. Way too long.\nFor several years, I was a regular donor. It was something I started after 9/11, when giving blood was considered a patriotic thing to do in case it was needed to treat survivors of those terrorist attacks or future ones.\n... I donated blood this week for the first time in a long time. Way too long.\nFor several years, I was a regular donor. It was something I started after 9/11, when giving blood was considered a patriotic thing to do in case it was needed to treat survivors of those terrorist attacks or future ones.\n... (Paul Muschick) If you missed my column last month, I recounted how I was a regular blood donor when I lived in North Carolina but didn’t keep it up after moving to Pennsylvania in 2004. I meant to get back in the game and finally did after hearing about a program to recruit donors at Miller-Keystone.\nThe center started a marketing campaign to increase the number of donors with rare blood traits. That means they aren’t just A, B or O, but that their blood has unique qualities such as red cells that lack certain antigens. The blood center’s goal is to diversify the supply with donations from various racial and ethnic groups so it better matches the region’s demographics.\nDiversifying the blood supply would especially help people with sickle cell disease, which affects blacks, Hispanics and people of Middle Eastern, Asian, Indian and Mediterranean descent at higher rates. They often need transfusions because their blood cells can become stiff, sticky and hard, blocking vessels and causing pain.\nI don’t have rare blood, but every donation counts.\nCaine wasn’t the only person I heard from after my column. A few others also thanked me for getting the word out, including a Breinigsville man who, like me, had been a regular donor while living elsewhere but stopped after moving to the Lehigh Valley. My story motivated him to start giving again. I hope others started, too.\nCaine said that every once in a while, he’ll get a call from Miller-Keystone asking if he will donate platelets because of an urgent need. And he obliges.\nHe does all this despite the fact he hates needles. Not just hates them, but hates them so much that he once left a movie theater after watching a scene involving one.\nIf he can get over that fear to make a difference in the lives of others, you can, too.\nYou can schedule a blood donation at 800-223-6667 or giveapint.org .\npaul.muschick@mcall.com\n610-820-6582\nPaul Muschick’s columns are published Monday through Friday at themorningcall.com and Sunday, Wednesday and Friday in The Morning Call. Follow me on Facebook at PaulMuschickColumns , Twitter @mcwatchdog and mcall.com/muschick .\n'It's unimaginable': 3 dead, 4 rescued after Grand Canyon helicopter crash Eagles offensive coordinator Frank Reich named Colts head coach; Birds face crucial decisions Braden Airpark getting face-lift, more attention from Lehigh-Northampton Airport Authority",
