        "title": "BID-P not feeling the blood pinch",
        "text": "BID-P not feeling the blood pinch Wednesday Feb 7, 2018 at 8:00 AM Feb 8, 2018 at 1:53 PM Flu season may be impacting platelet and blood donations regionally, but supplies haven’t showed any signs of drying up at the local hospital. Rich Harbert rharbert@wickedlocal.com @richharbertOCM \nPLYMOUTH – Flu season may be impacting platelet and blood donations regionally, but supplies haven’t showed any signs of drying up at the local hospital. \nJoanne Thibodeau, a clinical specialist working in the blood bank at BID-Plymouth hospital, said the hospital continues to receive shipments of blood and platelets from the American Red Cross every Monday, Wednesday and Friday. And if there is a run on supplies, the hospital can request additional units for other daily supply deliveries during the week. \nThe hospital used 255 units of blood in December. That is the second highest amount of transfused units in a month in 2017. The hospital transfused 256 units last March. \nThibodeau said there are times of the year when New England tends to be in a position to help other areas of the country that find themselves in need of blood because of hurricanes, tornadoes and other natural disasters. \nShe noted that winter storms and flu season can create shortages that leave New England hospitals vulnerable to shortages. \n“At Plymouth, we always seem to get the products even when there is a shortage. Usually the American Red Cross will call other areas and if they can’t supply we will call the Rhode Island Blood Center or the Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center and they would supply us with the product we need,” Thibodeau said. \nMost of the blood and platelets used at the local hospital are used in the oncology department and for in-patient therapy. \n“We haven’t had a really critical episode for a long time. A few years back we couldn’t get any. For some reason, we had no blood, but so far we don’t have that issue any more,” Thibodeau said. \nPlatelets can sometimes be harder to get because they have a shorter shelf life. Red blood cells, used for trauma, surgery, premature births and sickle cell and other blood disorders, have 42-day shelf life. \nPlatelets, used for cancer treatments and surgery, have a five-day shelf life. Plasma, used for burn patients, shock and bleeding disorders, can last up to a year if frozen. \nWhile demand for blood was high in December, demand for platelets was relatively low. \nThe hospital used 37 units of platelets last March and only 10 in December.",
