        "text": "Feb 8, 2018 at 1:20  20 PM \nFEB. 16-26 \nGIVE BLOOD \nDonations are needed \nMake an appointment at redcrossblood.org or 800-733-2767. Feb. 16: 9:30 a.m.-2:30 p.m. Monticello Government Center; Feb. 21: 2:30-7:30 p.m. Sullivan West High School; Feb. 22: 1-6 p.m. Port Jervis Elks Lodge; 1-7 p.m. Orange County Chamber of Commerce, Montgomery; Feb. 23: 2-7 p.m., Town of Newburgh offices, 1496 Route 300; Feb. 24: 11 a.m.-3 p.m., American Legion, Monroe; Feb. 26: 2-6 p.m., LongHorn Steakhouse, Newburgh. \nFEB. 17 \nEAGLE PARTY \nAnd a benefit \nCome to Bethel for an Eagle Celebration Party at Catskill Distilling Company's Dancing Cat Saloon and co-sponsored by the Delaware Highlands Conservancy. It's in honor of the eagle migration passing through Sullivan County. There'll be live music, a birds of prey presentation, a bonfire, a photography show, raffles and prizes, including signed eagle photos, plus specialty cocktails sold to benefit the conservancy. 2037 Route 17B, Bethel, catskilldistilling.com, delawarehighlands.org. \nFEB. 18 \nMUSICAL STAGECRAFT \nCanadian band \nThe Andrew Collins Trio makes its Catskills debut and offers a sneak peek of its upcoming double album (one vocal/one instrumental) \"tongue and groove\" in a 7:30 p.m. show at the Ashokan Center. The Canadian band has garnered a lot of attention and praise for its roots, newgrass, folk and jazz work along with what critics are calling an \"energetic interplay of instruments on stage.\" Tickets $10-$15, ashokancenter.org \nFEB. 24 \nMAPLE SUGARING \n'Tis that season \nMaple sugaring season kicks off at Hudson Highlands Nature Museum with a Sugaring Off Celebration, 11 a.m.-3 p.m. and a whole month of maple sugar tours. Tours will be led by environmental educators and take place at the Outdoor Discovery Center. There's a lot of maple sugar fun going on including taste tests, tree tapping, special crafts and games, storytelling and more. Visit hhnm.org for details and tour registration. \n\nFIX IT \nDon't throw it away \nDon't trash it; repair it. That's the motto at Repair Cafe, where \"repair coaches\" show you how to fix things - lamps, toys, small appliances, clothing, etc. Most repairs are free. They do it for you and/or show you the technique. This month, a repair cafe will be held at the Gardiner Library, 133 Farmer's Turnpike, noon-4 p.m. Find out more and see upcoming dates and locations at repaircafehv.org Never miss a story \nChoose the plan that's right for you. Digital access or digital and print delivery.",
