        "title": "Shock survey shows we donated fewer organs than anywhere else in country",
        "text": "Shock survey shows we donated fewer organs than anywhere else in country The East Midlands gave 74 organs for donation in a year Share Click to play Tap to play The video will start in 8 Cancel Play now Get Daily updates directly to your inbox + Subscribe Thank you for subscribing! Could not subscribe, try again later Invalid Email \nA Cystic Fibrosis sufferer whose life was saved by a lung transplant has urged people in the East Midlands to join the donor register. \nCharlotte Davis has made the appeal after new figures show that residents in the region donated the lowest number of organs in the country. \nCharlotte, 24, said: “Organ donation is an incredible act of kindness. Surgeon and nurse suture patient (Image: Getty) \n“In 2011 my life was saved thanks to my amazing donor and her family, who agreed to fulfil my donor’s wish to donate in the event of death. \n“Struggling to breathe due to Cystic Fibrosis, my lung transplant gave me the chance to graduate from university, jump out of a plane and enjoy every moment life gives. \n“Without organ donation I would have died at 18 years old. “I urge everyone who has the desire to sign up to the register, to do so and please share your wishes with your loved ones.” Read More Social media 'ghost policies' leaving thousands driving without car insurance \nThe figure for the East Midlands represents just 15.8 people per million donating organs during that year - the lowest percentage in England. \nThe report showed that people in the North-West gave the highest number of organs - 162, representing 22.6 donors per million. Doctor in operating theatre (Image: Getty) \nThis per capita figure was topped by the North-East where 28.6 people per million donated - the highest figure nationwide. Read More \nThe same survey revealed that the number of deceased organ donors rose to 1,413, a four percent increase on the previous year . \nIn addition, there were 1,043 living donors. Kidneys are important for blood purification in the body (Image: Getty) \nThis saw 753 live-saving and life-transforming transplants being performed by surgeons. \nIt was also revealed that the NHS succeeded in reaching a milestone figure, with 50,000 people alive today thanks to a transplant. Read More Fresh winter weather warning issued in Leicester for the weekend \nHowever, there were 6,388 patients waiting for a life-saving transplant in 2017. \nSadly, 457 patients died while waiting for their transplant on the active list, while 875 were removed from the list altogether. \nThe removals were mostly due to deteriorating health and ineligibility for transplant – with many of these patients passing away shortly after. \nThe North West was found to donate the most kidneys and cardiothoracic organs. \nWhile pancreas donation numbers are highest in the West Midlands, the East of England is highest for liver donations. \nThe statistics were revealed in research carried out for the fitness experts Nuyoo , using the NHS Organ Donation and Transplantation Activity Report for 2016/17. Like us on Facebook ",
