        "title": "On Facebook, she offered to donate her kidney. She found a recipient",
        "text": "She went on Facebook and offered to donate her kidney. She found someone who needs it Mike Argento , margento@ydr.com Published 12:33 p.m. ET Feb. 8, 2018 CLOSE Lisa Little's kidney, nicknamed Mabel, loved running. Before becoming a living donor, Little wanted to run one last 5K with Mabel. Kate Penn Buy Photo Kim Naill Storm, inspired by her father, decided to donate a kidney to a needy recipient. She found a donor, on Facebook. (Photo: Paul Kuehnel, York Daily Record) Buy Photo CONNECT COMMENT EMAIL MORE Sixteen years ago, Kim Naill Storm's family gathered in a small room at the Hershey Medical Center for a meeting with a doctor. Her father, David Naill, had been in a car accident near Dillsburg while on his way to work at Penske Truck Leasing on Jan. 18, 2002. He had been on life support in the hospital for 13 days, and the family had to review its options. They decided to take David off life support and allow him to go home. The family had a deep faith. David had been active in their Pentecostal church, and his reward for this life lay at the end. The doctors talked to the family about organ donation. David wasn't an organ donor and the doctors told the family that if they wished, they could make the decision for him, that his organs could live on to save lives, or at least make some lives more tolerable. The family didn't discuss it much, still in shock from the possibility of losing David. They went with what they believed David's wishes would have been and declined to donate his organs. Had he wanted to donate his organs, they reasoned, he would have designated that on his driver's license. More: Joseph Stalin's daughter lived in East Berlin, briefly Over the years, Kim, now 42 and living south of Hanover and working at Sweet Frog in town, thought about her family's decision. In the moment, it was a tough decision to make, clouded by the grief and shock the family was feeling at the time of David's untimely death at the age of 50. With time, though, she came to believe that it would have been a good thing to do to donate his organs. The joy it would have given other families would not have lessened their grief. But knowing that something good could have come from his death could have helped them heal as time passed. Occasionally, Kim would mention to friends and family that she was thinking about donating a kidney to someone in need. She would say it in passing, nothing too serious. She just thought she'd like to have a chance to do that, to help someone else out. It was just something she wanted to do. And she wanted to do it while she was still alive. She didn’t like the idea that her family's sorrow and grief could be someone else's joy. It was in the back of her mind when she saw a Facebook post from a friend asking people to post their bucket list items. Among the different dreams and aspirations – climbing mountains, running marathons and such – was Kim's post. Her bucket list was short. She wanted to donate a kidney to somebody in need. She signed up for the tests at the Hershey Medical Center. She passed all of them, except one – the psychological exam, necessary because, as Kim said, it's not common that people volunteer to have a surgeon cut into a healthy body and remove a vital organ. The test, though, hung her up. Like many people, she takes anti-depressants, and that fact caused the doctors to pause. The doctors told her she could donate blood, or bone marrow, and make a difference that way. As Kim said, \"I wanted to go bigger.\" Kim had been so committed to donating a kidney, the news was devastating. She cried all the way home. CLOSE Kim Storm describes how the decision to make a living organ donation began when her father was taken off life support. Paul Kuehnel Kim, undaunted, looked into private donation. Instead of donating a kidney that would go to the next person on the transplant list who matched her blood and tissue type, she could find somebody who needed a kidney and just donate it directly, by-passing some of the red tape and the psychological testing. More: A York County chainsaw carver's photo keeps showing up on dating sites. But it's not him. She didn't know anyone personally who needed a kidney. So she took to Facebook, and on Feb. 1, on the Hanover Helps page, posted: \"Serious post. I am looking to donate my kidney to a recipient in need. If you know somebody that could use a Type A positive kidney, please reach out to me. All necessary testing has already been completed by me. Thank you.\" It took a few days, but she found someone. *** Harry Rinehart developed kidney disease about five years ago. The disease progressed, and for the past three and a half years, he has been on dialysis. He developed other complications and recently wound up in the hospital with a sepsis infection. He needs a new kidney and has been on the transplant list for three years now, his wife, Joann, said. The list is long, much longer than the number of available kidneys. So all he could do was wait. Now and then, Joann would post updates of her husband's health on Facebook, asking friends to send their prayers. The Rineharts lean on their faith to get them through the days. Harry, 63, is a Pentecostal preacher. More: See YDR's latest subscription offer A Facebook friend – someone Joann went to school with but hadn't seen in decades – sent her a link to Kim's Facebook post offering a kidney. The friend is Kim's husband's aunt and just happened to know the Rineharts and their plight, learning about it on Facebook. Joann got in touch with Kim via Facebook Messenger. They spoke on the phone. It appears Harry and Kim might be a match, but they have to undergo more tests to make sure. And Harry has to recover from his complications. It could be a few months before he gets Kim's kidney. If it all works out, Kim would get to fulfill her wish. And Harry would get a new lease on life. *** Kim says her family supports her decision. \"Nobody's said 'don't do it,' not that it would matter anyway because I feel so strongly about it,\" she said. She has no fear of surgery. Though she was raised Pentecostal, she drifted from the faith. Her quest to donate a kidney has restored her faith, strengthened when she learned that the Rineharts share her faith. Joann Rinehart says Kim's offer is humbling. \"It's so unselfish, that somebody you don't know would give you a part of her body,\" Joann said. \"It's amazing.\" She said, \"We've been praying and waiting for a kidney for three years and along comes Kim. Just goes to show you that God works in mysterious ways.\" Reach Mike Argento at 717-771-2046 or at mike@ydr.com. Facebook ",
