        "text": "Church Events around Delaware County Posted: # Comments \nTurning Point Ministries: 624 E. Eighth St., Chester, is currently collecting food as part of its endeavor to continually build up the city. Congregants are willing to pick up any and all donated nonperishable items that can be stored in the church’s pantry until the time comes to serve. The pantry is opened the first and third Wednesdays of every month. For information and to set up donations, call LeeVetta Smith at 267-475-7087 or email turningpointministries7@gmail.com \nGrace Community UMC: 1213 Central Ave., Chester. The church Community Resource and Empowerment Center’s Fast Track 2 Success ten-week STEM program, with tutoring, life skills, and more, is now in its second of three sessions for the academic year. Classes run 10 a.m.-noon Saturdays. For information, call James Harper at 302-588-2467. \nThe Blue Church: 940 Baltimore Pike, Springfield, holds its annual Valentine Dinner on Saturday. Doors open at 5:30 p.m. Tickets are $60 per \ncouple. Philadelphia comedian Gordon Douglas is the keynote speaker, sharing about the things he wish he knew before he said “I do” as well things he has learned about making a marriage last. For tickets, call 610-544-3122. Advertisement \nChrist Episcopal Church: 311 South Orange Street, Media, announces that its chili cook off scheduled for Saturday is postponed. The new date is to be announced. \nGod’s House of Glory Haven of Peace: 900 E. Ninth St., Chester, hosts Widener University’s College Access Center at 11 a.m. Saturday. Representatives discuss college opportunities and other things the center has to offer. For information, call the church at 610-876-7764. \nHolmes Presbyterian Church: Holmes Road and Academy Avenue, holds its annual Soup Luncheon/Bake Sale from 11:30 a.m.-1:30 p.m. Saturday. Soups include: chicken escarole, chili, chicken noodle, vegetable beef and chicken corn chowder. Cost for lunch is $5.50 and includes a bowl of soup, roll/crackers and a beverage. All proceeds benefit the Holmes Youth Group; the church holds a spaghetti dinner, bake sale and silent auction fundraiser from 4:30-7:30 p.m. Saturday, March 3. Cost is $10 for adults, $5 for children under 12. The church continues the Eagles Super Bowl celebration by guests wearing Eagles attire getting $1 off admission. Dinner includes a beverage, bread, salad and spaghetti dinner. The spaghetti sauce is a homemade meat sauce with mushrooms. For information, call 610-532-0346. \nNorth Chester Baptist Church: 2331 Providence Ave., welcomes the Jacobs Brothers for a concert at 7 p.m. Saturday. In addition to touring in concert, the Dillsburg, Pa.-based group also host a weekly TV program and an annual gospel music festival at The King’s Campground near Gettysburg. For information, call 610-874-7948. \nFirst Baptist Church of Darby: 925 Summit St., holds its annual Building Fund Rally at 3:30 p.m. Sunday. The theme is “Which Foundation are you Building On” (Matthew 7:24-27). The event features the Rev. Quincy Hobbs, Guest Pastor of Zion Hill Baptist Church, Philadelphia, joined by his choir, ushers and parishioners. For information, call the church at 610-586-0179 or visit www.firstbaptistdarby.org \nSt. Gabriel Church: 233 Mohawk Ave., Norwood, hosts the Ridley Area Catholic Churches Lenten Series talks for 2018 entitled “The Ten Commandments.” The first installment is at 7 p.m. Tuesday, Feb. 13. The program consists of evening prayer, Benediction, and a talk entitled “I am the Lord your God; My Name is holy.” The Rev. Dennis Carbonaro, Director of Spiritual Formation (College Division), St. Charles Borromeo Seminary, is the speaker. A social follows the program. All are invited to attend. Please bring a friend. \nSt. Joseph Parish: 500 Woodlawn Ave., Collingdale, holds an American Red Cross blood drive from 2-7 p.m. Friday, Feb. 16, in the parish hall. For registration, call 1-800-red-cross or visit www.redcrossblood.org and enter code “St. Josephs Collingdale.” \nCalvary Baptist Church: 1616 W. Second St., Chester, presents its annual Scholarship Luncheon at 1 p.m. Saturday, Feb. 17, with the theme “Black Women Who Rock.” The luncheon was rescheduled from its original date, Feb. 10. All tickets almost purchased are honored for the new date. \nHoly Myrrh-Bearers Eastern Catholic Church: 900 Fairview Road, Swarthmore, resumes its bi-weekly pierogie sales in February. Orders are now being accepted. Cost is $8 a dozen. Order by the following Sunday for Friday pickup that week: Feb. 18; March 4, 18; April 1, 15, and 29, May 13 and 27, June 10. To order, call 610-544-1215 or email hmbchurch@verizon.net; The church has made its “Food & Clothing Collection for the Needy” a permanent ministry of the parish. Anyone wishing to donate any canned or boxed, non-perishable food items, good cold-weather clothing, unused personal items such as toiletries such as toothpaste, tooth brushes, wet wipes liquid hand soap and sanitizer, shampoo, deodorant and the like, should bring them to the church on any Saturday from 4-6 p.m. or on Sunday between 9 a.m.-noon, or use the drop-off box at the entrance to the Educational Center anytime during the week. \nBeacon of Hope Clothes Closet: located on the top floor of Olivet Presbyterian Church, 1001 Washington Ave., Prospect Park, holds its semi-annual Bag Sales on Thursday night March 1 from 6-8 and Saturday, March 3 from 9 a.m.-noon. \nChrist United Methodist Church: 600 E. Dutton Mill Road, Brookhaven, holds free community dinners and opens its food bank on the fourth Wednesday of each month. Dinners are held 5:30-7 p.m. The schedule for 2018 is: Feb. 28, March 28, April 25, May 23, June 27, no dinners in July or August, Sept. 26, Oct. 24, no dinners in November or December. Come out for food and fellowship, and bring neighbors. Good food. Come and bring your neighbors. The church’s food bank opens 11 a.m.-noon. For information, call the church at 610-874-1270. \nChrist Tabernacle Church: 14 S. Morton Ave., Morton, open its food pantry — which gives away five days’ worth of boxed and canned foods — every second and fourth Saturday of the month. Hot meals are also served. For information, call 610-328-2330. \nCollenbrook United Church: 5290 Township Line Road, Drexel hill, hosts a free monthly Community Dinner to help feed local families in need from 5-7 p.m. the last Thursday of each month in the fellowship hall. Guests should use the entrance near the playground; there is handicapped access through the sanctuary doors. For information, call 610-789-9590. \nDrexel Hill United Methodist Church: 600 Burmont Road, Drexel Hill, has begun a new outreach program: Project Reach, Service, Care. A free, catered community lunch along with a free clothing and hygiene-products cupboard are provided 11:30 a.m.-1 p.m. the fourth Saturday of every month, at the church. All are welcome. \nFirst Baptist Church of Oakeola: 600 W. Oak Lane, Glenolden, hosts zumba classes 6-7 p.m. every Monday and Wednesday. Cost is $7. For information, visit www.oakeola.compassion-ministries.com or call 610-583-5277. \nFirst United Methodist Church: 350 W. State St., Media, offers a free yoga for beginners class 10 a.m. Wednesdays. Donations welcome. For information, call 610-566-3172 or visit www.mediamethodist.org \nImago Dei Metropolitan Community Church: 1223 Middletown Road, Glen Mills, holds Silent Meditation 3 p.m. Sundays. The gatherings are an opportunity to silently reflect for up to one hour on spiritual principles that are especially appropriate for those who are in recovery or seeking healing. For information, call 610-358-1716 or Pastor@ImagoDeiMCC.org \nMedia Church of Christ: 423 Jackson St., has thousands of clothing items available for free until gone. Hours are 10 a.m.-2 p.m. Sundays, and at 7 p.m. Wednesdays. Anyone is welcome. \nProspect Park United Methodist Church: Holds Mom’s Morning Out nursery school for ages 18 months and up 9 a.m.-noon Monday-Wednesday and Friday. Cost is $15 per day. Activities include crafts, music, circle time and organized play. For information and registration, call 484-540-3132. \nNorwood United Methodist Church: Chester Pike and West Ridley Avenue. Little Blessings Christian Preschool is a part-time, Christian preschool, holds classes 9 a.m.-noon Monday-Friday, for ages 3-5. The school recommends a 3 day or 5 day program, but is flexible and works with parents’ schedules. Enrollment is open throughout the year until reaching maximum capacity. For information, call 610-583-4780 or email norwoodlittleblessings@yahoo.com \nSecond Baptist Church of Media: 400 E. State St., holds Bible study classes on Wednesday from 10:30-11:45 a.m. and 6:30-7:30 p.m. The text is “Distorted Images of God,” instructed by Pastor Warren D. Mays. Contact Pastor Mays if you plan to attend the morning or evening class at 610-565-0660 or wdmays@aol.com \nResurrection Life Church: The Church Street Thrift Shop opens 10 a.m.-2 p.m. on the first and second Saturdays of each month, September through June. The shop has clothing for all ages, housewares, shoes, baby items and more. The Church Street Thrift Shop is an outreach ministry of Resurrection Life Church. Donations of clothing and household items can be dropped off during shop hours or by calling 610-876-4062 for an appointment. \nSt. Joseph’s Church: Concord Road, Aston, holds Adult Scripture Study from 7-8:30 p.m. Tuesdays. This year’s topics are the letters of St. Paul to the Philippians, Colossians, Ephesians and the two letters to the Thessalonians. In these letters of encouragement, correction, and instruction written from prison, Paul lovingly inspires and offers challenges to greater discipleship. The classes offer greater understanding and in depth DVD presentations by scripture scholars. Cost of $20 includes a study guide. The class runs seven weeks with a break in Advent for optional study of the infancy narratives of Luke and Matthew, then resumes for an additional six weeks. For information, contact Ms. Maugeri at c.maugeri@comcast.net or 610-494-4358. \nSt. Luke CC Fellowship Hall: 320 Tilghman St., Chester, has new line dancing classes from 6-8 p.m. Mondays. Cost is $7. Come out and join the fun with beginner and intermediate dances. For information, 610-876-5197. \nWoodlyn Baptist Church: 1125 MacDade Blvd. The girls’ and boys’ clubs meet at 6:30 p.m. Sunday, with G.E.M.S. (Girls Everywhere Meeting the Savior) for grades 1-9 and C.S.B. (Christian Service Brigade) for boys in grades 1-12. Come out for team building, fun activities, crafts, life skills, achievement badges, service projects, sports, outdoor activities, mentoring and Bible lessons. Tadpoles group meets at the same time for children age 3 through kindergarten. Parents can come together and encourage their children’s physical, spiritual and social growth through games, crafts, play, and teachings from God’s word. For information, call 610-833-5577 or visit www.woodlynbaptist.org, www.facebook.com/woodlynbaptistchurch or follow the church on Twitter @WoodlynBaptist",
