        "title": "Church Services around Delaware County",
        "text": "Church Services around Delaware County Posted: # Comments \nC.C. Hancock United Methodist Church: 542 Wesley Road, Springfield, holds Sunday worship service at 10:30 a.m. This week is Boy Scout Sunday. There are no blood pressure screenings after the service this week. Makin’ Music is held Tuesday, Wednesday and Saturday; call 610-544-6986. Jazzercise is held Monday-Saturday; call 610-356-4685. For information, call 610-543-3551. \nChrist Episcopal Church: 311 S. Orange St., Media, offers Sunday Eucharist services at 8 and 10 a.m. The congregation is child friendly, with child care available starting at 9:30 and children welcome in the service. Christian Education for youth is held after 10 a.m. service and ends at 12:15 p.m. \nCornerstone Christian Ministries: 2914 W. Ninth St., Chester, holds Sunday morning worship service at 10. Bible study is Wednesday at 7 p.m. This Sunday, Pastor Paul A. Adams Sr. preaches at Providence Baptist Church, 1100 W. Second St., Chester, for its annual Deacon and Deaconess Day at 3:30, accompanied by the Praise and Worship Team, choir, ushers and congregation. \nFirst African Baptist Church: 901 Clifton Ave., Sharon Hill, celebrates Salute to Our Youth Sunday at 9:45 a.m. The Youth and Angelic choirs sing and the Youth Praise Dancers and Mime Ministry proclaim Christ through dance and mime. The Rev. Dr. Melvin McAllister, associate minister, preaches from the theme “God’s Got You Covered” (II Samuel 9:7-8). Sunday School and Discipleship classes for new members are at 8:45. Advertisement \nFirst United Methodist Church: 350 W. State St., Media, holds Adult Sunday School at 9, followed by Sunday worship at 10:15. Children’s Sunday School is held during the service, followed by refreshments and fellowship. Childcare is available. The Transition Town Media Free Store is located at FUMC and serves as a place to donate used items and take (for free) items that can be used or repurposed. \nGrace Community UMC: 1213 Central Ave., Chester, holds Sunday morning worship at 10:30. Sunday School is at 9:30. This week, Min. Esther Snow Newton God’s Word with the theme “Trust God” (Job 13:15 and Psalm 37:3-5). The GCUMC Youth for Christ Choir renders the music. Wednesday prayer session is at 2:30 p.m., followed by Bible study with Pastor John Lewis Sr. from 3-4. For information, call 610-876-6347. \nGod’s House of Glory Haven of Peace: 900 E. Ninth St., Chester, holds its African American History Celebration at 4 p.m. Sunday. For information, call 610-876-7764. \nInterboro Ministerium: Prospect Hill Baptist, Olivet Presbyterian and Immanuel Lutheran church hold Ash Wednesday worship at 7 p.m. Feb. 14 at Prospect Hill Baptist Church, 718 Lincoln Ave., Prospect Park. Pastor Chris Heisey-Terrell delivers the sermon with the theme “The Fast I Choose” (Isaiah 58:1-12). The service includes the imposition of ashes \nMemorial Presbyterian Church: holds worship and Lenten services at Linwood United Methodist Church, 1627 Chichester Ave., Linwood, at 1 p.m. Sunday, followed by fellowship hour. Lenten lunch is served on Wednesdays at noon beginning Feb. 14 in the Linwood UMC parish hall. Ash Wednesday service is at 6 p.m. Feb. 14. For information, call Judy at 215-292-4052. \nMiddletown Presbyterian Church: 273 S. Old Middletown Road, celebrates blended contemporary/traditional worship service at 10:30 a.m. This week, Pastor Douglas W. McPheeters continues his preaching series “Jesus of Nazareth: Who is He?” with the theme “Moses 2.0.” Sunday School for all ages is at 9, followed by coffee time and fellowship at 10. Adult Bible study is held Wednesdays from 9:30-11 a.m. The current book is Isaiah. The church observes Ash Wednesday on Feb. 14 with a soup supper at 6 p.m., followed by service of ashes at 7. For information, call the office at 610-565-4080 or visit www.middletownpres.org \nMount Sinai Baptist Church: 123 Bartram Ave., Lansdowne, celebrates 128 years of serving God and the community on Sunday, Feb. 25. Pastor Darnell Williams of Life in The Word Ministries, Delaware, is the guest speaker at the 11 a.m. service. Dinner is served immediately after the service. The Muriel King Concert Choir renders joyful gospel sounds in concert at 3:30 p.m. There is a free will offering. \nMt. Hebron AME Church: 1321 Green St., Linwood, holds a Day of Celebration on Sunday, Feb. 18. At 11 a.m., Pastor Belindia E. Boyer preaches for a Family and Friends Day worship service. The church’s Black History Celebration 3:30 p.m., with the Rev. Justin Powell of Greater Fountain Deliverance Ministries as the guest preacher. He is accompanied by the Bethel A.M.E. Church Praise Team of Wilmington, Del. Dinner is served from 1:30-3 p.m. \nProvidence Baptist Church: 1100 W. Second St., Chester, celebrates the Deacon and Deaconess Ministries’ Annual Day at 3:30 p.m. Sunday. The Rev. Paul Adams, Sr., pastor of Cornerstone Christian Ministry, is the guest preacher, accompanied by his choir and congregation. For information, call 484-66-3684 or email providencebaptistchurch1100@comcast.net \nTemple Baptist Church: 736 W. Seventh St., Chester, celebrates its 2018 Unity Day kickoff service at 3:30 p.m. Sunday with the Temple Choirs singing in unity. \nTemple of Brotherly Love CC Church: 1136 Highland Ave., Chester, celebrates Sunday service at 10:15 a.m. Wednesday night Bible study is at 7. For information, call 610-485-4980. \nTrainer United Methodist Church: 3705 W. Ninth St., welcomes Trinity United Methodist Church, due to a boiler issue at Trinity, for a joint service at 10 a.m. Sunday. The Rev. Jim Ford brings the message “Learning a Lesson About Love,” assisted by Bill Trader. Nursery and Junior Church are available. Ash Wednesday service with Holy Communion and ashes is at 7 p.m. Feb. 14, with the theme “The Mystery of the Incarnation.” Legacy Clothes Closet opens Friday from noon-2 p.m. Donations of food items are received weekday mornings for distribution through Food Cupboard. Donations are needed and greatly appreciated for the repair/replacement of the boiler at Trinity UMC, Eighth and Butler streets, Chester. \nTurning Point Ministries: 624 E. Eighth St., Chester, holds Sunday worship at 10:30 a.m. Bible study is Tuesday night at 7 via conference call; call 717-770-4160 and enter code 560016# (please mute phone during call). For information, call 610-490-9325 or visit www.tpmchester.org \nUnitarian Universalist Church of Delaware County: 145 W. Rose Tree Road, Media, holds Sunday worship at 9:30 and 11:15 a.m. This week, the spiritual theme of “Perseverance” continues with the topic “Fast or Far?” The Rev. Peter and Worship Associate Norma Lewis reflect on the proverb “If you want to go fast, go alone. If you want to go far, go together.” The UUCDC Chorus renders the music at both services. For information, visit www.uucdc.org or call the church office at 610-566-4853.",
