        "title": "Around Newburyport",
        "text": "Feb 9, 2018 at 8:00 AM \nUPCOMING \n“Dear Mr. Woodwell”: 7 p.m. Feb. 9; 2 p.m. Feb. 10, Amesbury High School auditorium, 5 Highland St. Tickets will available at door. Cost: $10 adults; $7 seniors and students. “Dear Mr. Woodwell” tells the story of AHS students who enlisted in World War II and corresponded with their favorite teacher, looking for news about their friends and hometown. Woodwell saved over 300 of these letters that he received from over 80 of his students. \n“The Last Five Years”: 8 p.m. Feb. 9 and 15; 1 p.m. Feb. 10, 11, 17 and 18; 5 p.m. Feb. 18, Firehouse Center for the Arts, Market Square, Newburyport. Cost: $15-$18. For information: 978-462-7336; http://firehouse.org. “The Last Five Years” is a musical written by Jason Robert Brown, directed by Stephen Faria, with musical direction by Alisa Bucchiere. It premiered at Chicago’s Northlight Theatre in 2001 and was then produced off-Broadway in March 2002. It has had numerous productions both in the U.S. and internationally. The story explores a five-year relationship between Jamie Wellerstein, a rising novelist, and Cathy Hiatt, a struggling actress. The show uses a form of storytelling in which Cathy’s story is told in reverse chronological order, and Jamie’s is told in chronological order. \nDark Desert Eagles — Eagles Tribute with Shun Ng: 8 p.m. Feb. 9, Blue Ocean Music Hall, 4 Oceanfront North, Salisbury. Cost: $19.50-$55.50. For tickets: 978-462-5888; 800-653-8000; http://BlueOceanHall.com; http://TicketMaster.com. \nMardi Gras Party: 7:30 p.m. Feb. 10, Cat in the Cradle Coffeehouse, 7 Central St., Byfield. Cost: $20. The BCAC presents a Mardi Gras Party, featuring King Carubia’s Hot Society Band. Come listen to the New Orleans-style brass band with influence of Dixieland, roaring ‘20s, hot jazz and traditional jazz. King Carubia’s Hot Society Band brings authentic NOLA jazz and it’s joyful noise to smiling faces throughout New England and the US. Dancing and good times guaranteed. Beer, wine, coffee, cold drinks and snacks will be for sale. Event sponsorships are $250. Sponsors will be included in all promotions and will receive preferred seating for four at the event. \nDuke Robillard concert: 8 p.m. Feb. 10, Firehouse Center for the Arts, Market Square, Newburyport. Cost: $22-$30. For information: 978-462-7336; http://firehouse.org. The Firehouse continues their Sea Level Oyster Bar Concert Series as they welcome blues guitarist Duke Robillard to their Institution for Savings Mainstage. \nBlood donation opportunity: 8 a.m.-1 p.m. Feb. 11, Latitude Sports Club, 191 Elm St., Salisbury. Make an appointment to give blood or platelets by downloading the free Red Cross Blood Donor App, visiting http://redcrossblood.org or calling 800-733-2767. More than 550 blood drives have been forced to cancel due to winter weather in January, causing over 16,500 blood and platelet donations to go uncollected. In Massachusetts, 28 blood drives have been forced to cancel due to winter weather this month, causing 750 donations to go uncollected. In addition, bitter cold and widespread flu have contributed to very low turnout at many blood drives. Every day, no matter the weather, the Red Cross must collect more than 13,000 blood and platelet donations to meet the needs of patients. \nA Tale of Two Beaches: 2-3 p.m. Feb. 11, Newburyport Public Library, 94 State St., Newburyport. Join for a series of presentations on various topics in local history. How did Plum Island and Salisbury Beach evolve from remote and inhospitable barrier beaches into beachfront destinations? Why do they have such distinct personalities? With the help of dozens of fascinating photos, maps, documents and postcards, presenter John Macone will explain “A Tale of Two Beaches.” Macone is the former editor of the Daily News of Newburyport and co-author of the book Plum Island and Salisbury Memories, and currently works as the development specialist for the Merrimack River Watershed Council. \nDel Sol Quartet: 4-5:30 p.m. Feb. 11, Unitarian Church, 26 Pleasant St., Newburyport. Cost: $10-$20. For information: frsuu.org/jean-wilson-music-series. Del Sol Quartet, hailing from San Francisco, has received Gramophone awards for adventurous chamber music and is known for lively and engaging performances. The performance will feature music by Samuel Barber, Stefano Scodanibbio, Frederick Rzewski, Gabriela Lena Frank and Lou Harrison. \n“The Lion King” screening: 5 p.m. Feb. 11, Firehouse Center for the Arts, Market Square, Newburyport. Cost: $5. For information: 978-462-7336; http://firehouse.org. Join the Firehouse Center for the Arts for a community screening of the Walt Disney movie “The Lion King.” Doors open at 4 p.m. for this all-ages event. Dinner will be provided by Otto Pizza, as well as snacks and drinks while being entertained by Zach Field Drum Studios. The film screening will then begin at 5 p.m. All proceeds will benefit the Divinity Foundation, as part of NYS’ trips to Kenya. Participants give aid to Kenyans in the areas of malaria prevention, personal hygiene, water filtration, and more. \nHiking the Bay Circuit Trail Video Journal: 7-8:30 p.m. Feb. 13, Newburyport Public Library, 94 State St., Newburyport. Dan and Marilyn Brielmann and Alan French will guide participants along the Bay Circuit Trail, a 200-mile natural wonder that arcs around the city of Boston from Newburyport to Kingston. There will be music, video and information about the Trail. There will also be time for questions. \nCivil War Roundtable of the Merrimack: 7:30-9:30 p.m. Feb. 14, East Parish Methodist Church, Salisbury Square, Salisbury. For information: http://cwrtmerrimack.org; 978-462-8518. The Civil War Roundtable of the Merrimack meeting will feature a Civil War “Show and Tell.” Participants will have an opportunity to present Civil War artifacts or discuss their ancestral involvement in the conflict. Admission is free and anyone with an interest in America’s Civil War is invited to attend. \n1970s Revisited — Would You Buy This House?: 6-7 p.m. Feb. 15, Custom House Maritime Museum, 25 Water St., Newburyport. The Newburyport Preservation Trust presents the second in its series of instructive preservation sessions. The session looks back at an early attempt to “do-over” an old house, circa 1750, in Newburyport during the ‘70s by one of its owners, local architect and Newburyport Preservation Trust Co-president Linda Miller. Miller moved to Newburyport in 1975. She founded the Newburyport Preservation Trust in 2004 in order to raise awareness of the unique, yet perishable heritage of this community’s residential and commercial structures. \nOccidental Gypsy concert: 8 p.m. Feb. 16, Firehouse Center for the Arts, Market Square, Newburyport. Cost: $17 members, students and seniors; $20 nonmembers. For tickets and information: http://firehouse.org/see-a-show/198-occidental-gypsy. The band features Eli Bishop, Brett Feldman, Jeremy Frantz, Jon Chapman and Jeff Feldman. \nBruce in the USA: 8 p.m. Feb. 17, Blue Ocean Music Hall, 4 Oceanfront North, Salisbury. Cost: $19.50-$55.50. For tickets: 978-462-5888; 800-653-8000; http://BlueOceanHall.com; http://TicketMaster.com. Cost: $20-$26. Springsteen tribute show. \nChildren’s Sports Camp: 6-8 p.m. Feb. 19-22, Market Street Baptist Church gym, 37 Market St., Amesbury. Cost: $10. Make check payable to “MSBC” and note “sports.” Registration will be held from 5:30-6 p.m. Feb. 19 at the church. To preregister, contact the church office at 978-388-0930, or email msbcsec@verizon.net. For information, visit msbcnews.org. Please note that no child will be turned away for financial reasons, so the Church will accept whatever is affordable. The Market Street Baptist Church is hosting a four-day Junior Church Sports Camp for children grades K-4. All are welcome to participate. The Camp features a non-competitive program designed to teach basic skills in basketball, baseball, floor hockey and soccer, as well as Bible knowledge in a fun and engaging manner. A different sport will be introduced each day. \nThrough My Eyes — Amesbury History: 7 p.m. Feb. 21, Amesbury Senior Community Center, 68 Elm St. Steve Klomps, member of the Amesbury Historic Commission, will lead off the program series “Through my Eyes — Amesbury History.” Klomps will use historic objects as a way to explore local history — a 17th-century brick from Jacob Morrill’s house, a silver spoon made by William Little, a woodworking plane from the boat shop of Frank Morrill and more. This program is free. \nMark Cohn concert: 8 p.m. Feb. 22, Blue Ocean Music Hall, 4 Oceanfront North, Salisbury. Cost: $35.50-$49.50. For tickets: 978-462-5888; 800-653-8000; http://BlueOceanHall.com; http://TicketMaster.com. \nShucking for Shelter Oyster Fundraiser: 5:30-7 p.m. Feb. 24, Starboard Galley, 55 Water St., Newburyport. Donations of $15 per person will be accepted at the door. Donations include a plate of three oysters. Additional oysters will be available for a small per-oyster price. Cash bar. Extra seating is available upstairs. Pennies for Poverty will host an Oyster Fundraiser at Starboard Galley to raise funds to support people struggling to pay for housing and utilities on the area. This annual event brings together Pennies’ community of people who care. Stop by for an appetizer before heading out to dinner. Join with others who want to make a difference in the community. \nVintage Vocal Quartet: 7 p.m. Feb. 24, Firehouse Center for the Arts, Market Square, Newburyport. Cost: $13 members; $15 nonmembers. For information: http://firehouse.org/see-a-show/239-vintage-vocal-quartet. The Vintage Vocal Quartet brings to life the harmonies of the big band era. \nSteve Hurl and Kirsten Manville concert: 7:30 p.m. Feb. 24, Cat in the Cradle Coffeehouse, 7 Central St., Byfield. Table seating is available. Beer, wine, coffee, cold drinks and snacks will be for sale. Event sponsorships are $250. Sponsors will be included in all promotions and will receive preferred seating for four at the event. \nOur Boy — Newburyport’s First WWI Casualty Finds His Way Home: 2-3 p.m. Feb. 25, Newburyport Public Library, 94 State St. The History Lecture Series is sponsored by the Newburyport Public Library, the NPL Archival Center and historian Ghlee Woodworth. Follow the journey of Eben “Bunny” Bradbury from his doorstep on Bromfield Street to the battlefields of France, and how the love and support of his hometown, a century later, helped to bring the story of “our boy” to life. \nSkipper’s Alley at Belleville Roots: 8 p.m. March 2, Belleville Stage, 300 High St., Newburyport. Tickets are $30 in advance; $35 day of show; and $10 ages 18 and younger. Tickets are available at Dyno Records, 1 Middle St., Newburyport; at the Belleville Congregational Church office from 9 a.m.-1 p.m. Tuesdays, Thursdays and Fridays; and at the Belleville Thrift Shop on from 9 a.m.-noon Wednesdays and Saturdays. For online tickets: http://brownpapertickets.com. Tickets will be available at the door, subject to availability. For information on the concert or music series: bellevilleroots@gmail.com; http://bellevilleroots.org. For information on the band, visit http://skippersalley.ie. Belleville Roots Music presents Skipper’s Alley, a traditional Irish band, in concert. Skipper’s Alley is a traditional Irish band from Dublin, Ireland, who specializes in gritty, high-octane Irish dance tunes on uilleann pipes, whistles, fiddle, bodhran, bouzouki and flute with occasional detours into the dark somber melodies of the irish song tradition. \nThe Halifax Collision: 2-3 p.m. March 4, Newburyport Public Library, 94 State St. On Dec. 6, 1917, during the height of the First World War, two ships trying to navigate Halifax Harbour collided resulting in the largest man-made explosion in the pre-atomic age. Essex Heritage Trustee David Read will recount the events leading up to this tragedy and the Massachusetts rescue effort. Relive the personal stories and riveting details of the weeks that followed, and learn about the important train to ever travel through Essex County. And learn why the citizens of Nova Scotia still send a special gift or appreciation each year. \nONGOING \n“Raptors” oil painting exhibit: noon-5 p.m. Wednesdays-Sundays, Jan. 31-Feb. 25, Institution for Savings Art Gallery, Firehouse Center for the Arts, Market Square, Newburyport. For information: 978-462-7336; http://firehouse.org.“Raptors” is an exhibit of detailed oil paintings by Jim Ryan, offering close-up looks into the patterns and natural colors found in the eyes and feathers of raptors. Ryan started painting only a few years ago at age 55. He is self-taught, working mainly in oils. He also uses watercolors, colored pencils, charcoal and graphite. He also does plein-air work. This is his first exhibit. Ryan grew up in Dorchester and currently lives in Merrimac. He works full time in training and development in the health care industry. He is a bird watcher, hiker and mountaineer. \nGlobal Citizenship Class: 3-5 p.m. Fridays, through February, Newburyport Youth Services, 40 Milk St. For information: sandra@smallsolutionsbigideas.org. The final class will be held on a Saturday morning. Registration is available online on Newburyport Youth Services website, or at the Milk Street office. In this program, youth share their lives and culture with peers in Kenya; they take on common challenges, and through understanding their own country, resources and culture, they can begin to imagine how to address the challenges of their future. Topics will include: “Our Community”— students will create narrative, photographic and video/audio information that portrays their community; “Our Future”— youth will share visions of their futures, their hopes and concerns; and “Youth Voices”— participants will share discussions, photos, videos and narratives with youth in the Small Solutions network of Kenyan communities. Sandra Thaxter and Laurel Hanke are the instructors. Parents are welcome to participate \n“Celebrate Good Times” by Jane Coder: 10 a.m.-7 p.m. Monday-Friday, through March 8. Carry Out Cafe & Catering, 155 State St., Newburyport. For information: https://facebook.com/events/2004583923098330/. Find a cure to the winter blues with the uplifting colors in the artwork by Jane Coder, now on display at Carry Out Cafe & Catering. The exhibition, titled “Celebrate Good Times,” features warm, vibrant and celebratory colors designed to contrast with the cold winter grays, whites and blacks outside. A reception will be held from 2-4 p.m. Feb. 4 at the Cafe. The public is invited to meet the artist, view the paintings and enjoy a custom beverage from the hot cocoa bar. \n“It’s Getting Late” by Leah Grimaldi: 8:30 a.m.-4 p.m. Tuesday-Sundays and Mondays holidays, through March 4, Joppa Flats, 1 Plum Island Turnpike, Newburyport. For information: 978-462-9998; http://massaudubon.org. Mass Audubon’s Joppa Flats Education Center presents an installation of contemporary artwork inspired by the beauty of Plum Island and the delicate global situation of all earthlings. Leah Grimaldi will be showing her cut-paper installation “It’s Getting Late.” Grimaldi is an artist who received her BFA from Pratt Institute and her MFA from Vermont College of Fine Arts. Her work, involving drawing, painting, cutting and sewing, explores nature and emotion in the context of the current culture. She currently lives in Salem. \nDave Ramsey Financial Series: 7-8:30 p.m. Mondays, Feb. 5-April 2, Hope Community Church, 11 Hale St., Newburyport. There is a cost for materials per person or couple. For information: 978-463-4673; http://hopenewburyport.com/shorttermgroups. The series “Financial Peace University” is a nine-session, DVD-based course with radio host Dave Ramsey. Learn how to eliminate debt and stress with workable spending and investment plans that address all the critical issues, including budgeting, house purchases and medical emergencies. \nRhythm N’ Roots Community Drum Circles: 7 p.m. first Friday of each month, People’s United Methodist Church, 64 Purchase St., Newburyport. There is a suggested $5 donation at the door. For information: 978-834-0367; http://imaginestudios.org. Presented by Imagine Studios. Participants will gather in a circle and share in the group rhythm making and song. Attendees are free to bring drums and percussion instruments, or they can play those provided. All ages and experiences are welcome. Refreshments are provided by The People’s Cafe. \nCommunity Open Mic: 7 p.m. last Friday of each month, People’s United Methodist Church, 64 Purchase St., Newburyport. There is a suggested $5 donation at the door. For information: 978-834-0367; kristine@imaginestudios.org; http://imaginestudios.org. Presented by Imagine Studios. Musicians, poets and performers of all ages, genres and abilities are welcome. Sign-up begins at 6:30 p.m. Refreshments are provided by The People’s Cafe. \nTai Chi at the Library: 9:05-9:50 a.m. Fridays, Newburyport Public Library, 94 State St., Newburyport. Improve physical and mental health by joining the free weekly drop-in tai chi class at the Newburyport Public Library. Barb Tindall will lead the class in tai chi and qigong in the form of Wu Dang as taught by Xuan Yun. No experience is necessary. Wear comfortable clothing. The program is funded by the Friends of the Newburyport Public Library \nLandings — A Safe Place to Land: Immaculate Conception Church, Nativity Church Hall, 42 Green St., Merrimac. Pre-registration is required. For information: 978-462-2724; mmckinnon@newburyportcatholic.org; 978-346-8604, ext. 7; reledhrp@gmail.com. This program is for Catholic individuals who have been away from the church. Holy Redeemer/Immaculate Conception Collaborative Parishes invites them to return to a more active practice of faith. Landings is a program that offers “a safe place to land,” a place for listening and for being heard, a place for asking questions and for reconnecting with the faith as an adult. \nNewburyport Choral Society ongoing rehearsals: 7:15-9:30 p.m. Mondays. Choral members range from high school to retirees joining together to perform concerts with professional orchestra and soloists. NCS presents two major choral concerts annually in December and May. For information: newburyportchoralsociety.org. \nLake Gardner Improvement Association meetings: 6:30 p.m. second Wednesday of each month, Code and Circuit Learning Lab, 36 Main St., Amesbury. For information: 373-388-3659; info@lgia.org. The Lake Gardner Improvement Association is an active advocacy group dedicated to promoting and protecting the lake. The public is welcome to join, get involved and help plan upcoming events. \nSouth Hampton Baptist Church worship and events: Wednesdays/Sundays, South Hampton Baptist Church, 10 Jewell St., South Hampton, New Hampshire. For information: 603-394-2224. South Hampton Baptist Church holds Sunday morning service 10:30-11:30 a.m.; Wednesday evening Bible study 6:30 to 7:30 p.m.; and game day every third Sunday beginning at noon. \nBelleville Congregational Church services: 10 a.m. Sundays, 300 High St., Newburyport. For information: 978-465-7734; http://bellevillechurch.org. The Rev. Ross Varney leads worship at 10 a.m. each Sunday in the chapel. Children experience a mixture of worship with family and classroom time. Refreshments and fellowship follow after the service. The youth choir rehearses after the service while the adult choir rehearses Thursdays at 7 p.m. Bible discussion is Thursdays at 6 p.m. The thrift shop is open Wednesdays and Saturdays, 9 a.m. to noon. The next Men’s Fellowship Dinner will be held at 6:30 p.m. Feb. 7. The guest speaker will be John Feehan, executive director YWCA. The topic will be white privilege. Women’s Coffee and Conversation will be held at 9 a.m. Feb. 10. Tickets on sale now for an Irish Evening Belleville Roots Music concert on March 2, featuring traditional Irish live music, dancers, Irish food and beverages — visit http://bellevilleroots.org \nMarket Street Baptist Church services and programs: Market Street Baptist Church, 37 Market St., Amesbury. For information: 978-388-0930; msbcsec@verizon.net; http://MSBCNews.org. The Rev. Michael John is the pastor; the Rev. Adam Davis is the associate pastor and music leader. Worship services begin at 10 a.m. Coffee Hour Fellowship follows worship. Nursery care during worship is available for ages 4 and younger. The Sunday worship service can be viewed on cable TV 22 at 7:30 a.m. and 5 p.m. Sermons can be heard on Word Radio WSEW 88.7 FM at 9 a.m. Junior Church for ages 5-9 during worship occurs twice a month. Communion Services are held every first Sunday of month. Men’s Bible Study is held at 7 p.m. Wednesdays. Women’s Bible study night is held from 11 a.m.-12:30 p.m. Wednesdays. Fellowship night meal and devotions are held from 5:30-6:30 p.m. and teaching from 6:30-7:30 p.m. Wednesdays — this includes Adult Bible Study, Youth Group for grade 5 and up; SHINE for girls grades K-4; and Boys on Mission for boys grades K-4. Worship can be seen on ACT12 TV and Port Media TV10 4:30 p.m. Thursdays. Worship can be seen on Act 12 TV at 9 a.m. Fridays. Office hours are 9 a.m.-noon Monday-Thursday, 11 a.m.-2 p.m. Fridays. \nDrum circle with Mamadou Diop: 6-7 p.m. Sundays, Tannery Dance Place, 50 Water St., #34, Newburyport. For information: 978-465-1485. The community is invited to drum with master Senegalese drummer Mamadou Diop every Sunday at the Tannery Dance Place. These low cost drum classes offer spiritual song, African rhythms in a supportive learning community. These classes are offered on a drop in basis for $15 per class, $10 to bring your own drum. \nParker Wheeler Sundays at The Grog: 7-11 p.m. Sundays, The Grog, 13 Middle St., Newburyport. Cost: $7. For information: 978-465-8008; http://thegrog.com. Parker Wheeler and Friends will perform 