        "text": "Tyndall registers possible bone marrow donors Friday Feb 9, 2018 at 4:04 PM Feb 9, 2018 at 4:04 PM COLLIN BREAUX News Herald Reporter @PCNHCollinB \nTYNDALL AIR FORCE BASE — Latia Wilkins was happy to give back earlier this week at Tyndall Air Force Base. \nWilkins, an airman at Tyndall, signed up for a bone marrow donation program that ended Friday on base. \n“I’m very compassionate and giving,” Wilkins said. “I think it’s a really wonderful thing to do. You don’t think about it until it happens to you. ... This is my first time registering, so I didn’t know anything about this until now. You can’t put a price on life. I’m excited to do it and I hope I’m a match.” \nDonors who sign up for the C.W. Bill Young Department of Defense Marrow Donor Program are contacted if they’re found to be a strong match. Wilkins and others were encouraging people to sign up Friday when they passed through the Base Exchange. \nThe program allows uniformed and civilian Department of Defense (DoD) personnel, as well as their dependents ages 18-60 to register, according to a post on Tyndall’s Facebook page. \n“Every year about 20,000 Americans are diagnosed with a life-threatening blood disease, something that can only be taken care of by a bone marrow donation,” said Master Sgt. Jason Gilbert, liaison between Tyndall and the program. “The DoD said we have a healthy population of young men and women ready to put themselves in harm’s way to help save lives. This is one extension we can use to be a life-saver for someone.” \nSince the program started in 1991, it has registered more than a million people, 75,000 of which were a probable match, Gilbert said. But out of those 75,000, only 7,000 have been “fully selected” to be a donor after more extensive research. There are no costs or “cut in leave” to the donor, he said. \nAbout 200 individuals have registered this week, Gilbert said. \n“What they do is fill out a contact sheet and health survey. And then they have four cotton swabs. The saliva from the cotton swabs is where the lab up in D.C. will get the human leukocyte antigen, and then it gets put into the registry.” \nThis week’s drive was “a blessing” since airmen are helping save lives, he added. \nShauna Sokolowski, a Tyndall pediatric nurse who urged people to sign up Friday, has firsthand experience with how it feels to participate since she’s donated marrow. \nSokolowski signed up several years ago through Yokota Air Base in Japan and later got a call to donate. Her marrow went to a young girl whose immune system couldn’t fight infections, and though Sokolowski doesn’t know exactly how the girl’s health turned out afterward, she’s confident everything worked out well. \n“For her it would have been a cure,” Sokolowski said. “I assume it would have went well.” Never miss a story \nChoose the plan that's right for you. Digital access or digital and print delivery.",
